commit b97781cd430d910b1f32619a3c0fd808a00c586d
Author: Moshe Abramovitch <moshea@nvidia.com>
Date:   Mon Jun 1 13:46:12 2026 -0500

    chore(sync): use rolling tracker for sync-failure issues

    Today's sync workflow opens a fresh GitHub issue every time a sync
    run encounters a partial component failure OR a total workflow
    failure. That accumulates noise — 30 sync-failure issues piled up
    in the past two weeks, each a snapshot of a single run, none
    actionable after the next sync.

    Replaces the two issue-creation steps with a single "rolling
    tracker" pattern that mirrors how the missing-compliance tracker
    already works (lines 230-280 of this file):

    - If the current run is clean (no failed components, no job
      failure): close the existing tracker if one is open.
    - If the current run has failures: update the existing tracker in
      place with current state, or open a new one if none exists.

    Net effect: at most ONE open sync-failure issue at any time,
    auto-updating each run, auto-closing when sync recovers. Matches
    the missing-compliance tracker behavior — single source of truth,
    not a per-run log.

    No change to sync logic or to what gets reported — same data,
    different lifecycle.

    Signed-off-by: Moshe Abramovitch <moshea@nvidia.com>
